Import Libraries
import nltk
Imports the NLTK (Natural Language Toolkit) library.
Used for text processing tasks like tokenization, stemming, POS tagging, etc.

from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
Imports the word_tokenize() function.
Used to split a sentence into individual words/tokens.
Example:
"Hello world"
becomes
['Hello', 'world']

from nltk.corpus import stopwords
Imports stopwords list.
Stopwords are common words like is, the, and, of which usually do not add important meaning.

from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer, WordNetLemmatizer
Imports:
PorterStemmer() → for stemming
WordNetLemmatizer() → for lemmatization

from nltk import pos_tag
Imports POS (Part Of Speech) tagging function.
Used to identify noun, verb, adjective, etc.

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
Imports TF-IDF vectorizer from Scikit-learn.
Used to convert text documents into numerical form.

PART 1 : TEXT PREPROCESSING
text = "Text analytics is the process of analyzing text data to extract useful information."
Stores the sample sentence in variable text.

print("========== TEXT PREPROCESSING ==========\n")
Prints heading.

print("----- ORIGINAL TEXT -----")
print(text)
Displays original sentence.

Tokenization
tokens = word_tokenize(text)
Splits sentence into words/tokens.

Example output:

['Text', 'analytics', 'is', 'the', ...]
print("\n----- TOKENS -----")
print(tokens)
Prints all tokens.

POS Tagging
pos = pos_tag(tokens)
Assigns grammatical tags to each word.
Example:
('Text', 'NN')
NN means Noun.

print("\n----- POS TAGS -----")
Prints heading.
for word, tag in pos:
Loops through every word and its POS tag.

print(f"{word:<12} -> {tag}")
Prints word and tag in formatted style.
Example:
analytics   -> NNS

Stopword Removal
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
Loads English stopwords into a set.
Example:
is, the, of, to
filtered = [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in stop_words]
Removes stopwords from tokens.
Logic:
word.lower() converts word to lowercase.
Checks whether word is NOT in stopwords.
Keeps only meaningful words.

print("\n----- AFTER STOPWORD REMOVAL -----")
print(filtered)
Prints filtered words.

Stemming
stemmer = PorterStemmer()
Creates stemming object.
stemmed = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in filtered]
Converts words to root form.
Example:
analyzing → analyz
information → inform
print("\n----- STEMMED WORDS -----")
print(stemmed)
Prints stemmed words.

Lemmatization
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
Creates lemmatizer object.
lemmatized = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in filtered]
Converts words into meaningful dictionary base form.
Example:
cars → car
running → running

Difference:
Stemming may produce incomplete words.
Lemmatization gives proper meaningful words.

print("\n----- LEMMATIZED WORDS -----")
print(lemmatized)
Prints lemmatized words.

PART 2 : TF-IDF
documents = [
"Text analytics is useful",
"Text data analysis is important",
"Analytics helps extract information"
]
Creates list of documents.
Each sentence is treated as one document.

print("\n\n========== TF-IDF REPRESENTATION ==========\n")
Prints heading.

print("----- DOCUMENTS -----")
Prints heading for documents.

for i, doc in enumerate(documents, 1):
Loops through documents.

enumerate(...,1) starts numbering from 1.

print(f"Doc {i}: {doc}")
Prints each document with number.

TF-IDF Vectorization
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
Creates TF-IDF vectorizer object.

tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(documents)
Main Logic:
Learns all important words from documents.

Calculates:

TF (Term Frequency)
IDF (Inverse Document Frequency)
Converts text into numeric matrix.

features = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
Gets all unique words/features.
Example:
['analysis', 'analytics', 'data', 'extract']
matrix = tfidf_matrix.toarray()
Converts sparse matrix into normal array.

print("\n----- FEATURE NAMES -----")
print(features)
Prints all feature words.

print("\n----- TF-IDF MATRIX -----")
print("Rows = Documents, Columns = Words\n")
Prints matrix heading.

for i in range(len(matrix)):
Loops through each document row.

print(f"Doc {i+1}:")
Prints document number.

for j in range(len(features)):
Loops through each feature word.

print(f"{features[j]:<12} : {matrix[i][j]:.3f}")
Prints TF-IDF score of every word.

.3f means show 3 decimal places.

Example:
analytics : 0.423

